 is one of the first program that any new programmer learns. It's a simple way of ensuring that the program you're writing is working as it should and can successfully output some text to the console.

For most languages, "Hello World" looks like this:

```
public class HelloWorld {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("Hello World");
    }
}
```

In the above code, the `public class HelloWorld` declares the class. `public static void main(String[] args)` is the main function that runs when the program starts. `System.out.println("Hello World")` outputs the text "Hello World" to the console.

In Python, "Hello World" is a bit simpler as it doesn't require a class or a main function:

```
print("Hello World")
``

A classic first program!

In many programming languages, the first "Hello, World!" program is a simple print statement that outputs the string "Hello, World!". It's often used as a starting point for beginners to learn the basics of a new language.

Here's an example in Python:
```
print("Hello, World!")
```
And here's one in Java:
```java
public class HelloWorld {
  public static void main(String[] args) {
    System.out.println("Hello, World!");
  }
}
```
